<br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1" alt=""/></span></td>
<td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%">
<p>A lot of healing depends on your tanks hitpoints and also the situation. If you are going up against red mobs and they hit a good majority harder than you are used to, you are going to have to heal a lot sooner. As you gain levels and get much higher you have to start healing sooner and sooner. I usually cast Complete Heal at around 50-60% at my level now. In the higher levels a LOT depends on the ability of the other people in your group. There is no way you are going to be able to heal your tank at 20 or 30% when you get into the planes. They just hit too hard. I suggest healing at around 50% when you get complete heal. In the lesser/older zones you can get away with 40 and 30% Complete heals. Truthfully I had a hard time healing and not going low on mana until I hit 39. Complete Heal really is a godsend to a cleric's mana. It helps a great deal in preserving mana and being able to have the extra mana when needed for those tough situations. At the lower levels I pretty much just spam healed the tank and tried to conserve as much mana as possible. When you are able to start gaining AA experience, it helps a LOT in keeping the tank and others in your group/raid healed while also reducing the amount of mana taken by healing spells.  <br /> <br />As for spell slots, as of right now I have Complete Heal, 2 Fast heals just in case I need to make the tank stable enough to cast Complete heal on him/her or saving the casters that get aggro. Then I have my best Heal over Time spell and then always my latest hitpoint buff. Usually some utility slots for whatever the occasion calls for. <br /> <br />Also, another thing to remember about healing, timing and percentage is that if your tank is low on health after the end of a fight and you dont have a lot of time to cast a Complete heal on him or her you can cast a Heal over Time on them to boost their health some. This comes into play when there is a pull coming right after the death of another mob. Heal over time spells create a much lower amount of aggro then a direct heal, so you should be safe to then cast a better heal on the tank when they have proper aggro. Now if you direct heal when the mob is incoming and the tank hasnt established aggro yet this is a sure way to get instant aggro. So, you want to be aware of that. <br /> <br />I hope this helped some and it should help you out as you gain levels and get higher in the game.</p>
<br /><span class="sm">----------------------------</span><br />Diviner Fildawen Blueillusion <br />66 Cleric on Mithaniel Marr</td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td class="fs8"></td></tr></table></td></tr></table>
